</div><a id="comment-2078343"></a>


<div  id="comment-2078343" class="comment comment-published clear-block">
      <div class='column-top'><div class='column-wrapper'>
  
      <div class='comment-submitted clear-block'> <div class='byline'>Posted by <span class='username'>Mairead</span></div><div class='date'>Mar 14 2012 - 6:21pm</div></div>
  
      </div></div>
  
      <div class='column-main'><div class='column-wrapper'>
  


      <div class='comment-content clear-block prose'>
      <p>Most people would probably recognise a distinction between everyday life and an emergency situation where the good of all must temporarily take precedence over the rights of the individual.  People adrift in a lifeboat would be a good example:  food would want rationing, and an individual who asserted his pre-lifeboat right to eat as much as he liked might well find himself on the menu instead.</p>
<p>The Greeks even institutionalised the emergency suspension of (what they called) democracy, allowing someone to be named Dictator for a period not to exceed five years (I think it was five years).  During his office, the Dictator ruled by fiat and no law applied unless he agreed it.  But there were no extensions allowed, and if he hadn't stepped down when his time was up he was quite likely to be killed as a usurper.</p>
<p>We're certainly in such an emergency situation right now, and it'll only get worse unless we fix it.</p>
    </div>
      <div class='comment-links clear-block'><ul class="links"><li class="comment_forbidden first last"><span><a href="/user/login?destination=node%2F80387%23comment-form">Login</a> or <a href="/user/register?destination=node%2F80387%23comment-form">register</a> to post comments</span></li>
