<div  id="comment-2077960" class="comment comment-published clear-block">
      <div class='column-top'><div class='column-wrapper'>
  
      <div class='comment-submitted clear-block'> <div class='byline'>Posted by <span class='username'>Peace Czar</span></div><div class='date'>Mar 14 2012 - 12:37pm</div></div>
  
      </div></div>
  
      <div class='column-main'><div class='column-wrapper'>
  


      <div class='comment-content clear-block prose'>
      <p>Agreed.  I'm in eastern PA and while I simply used the woods near me for running and hiking, hunting is a reality of the rural landscape.  If a deer is going to end up either roadkill or the meat supply for a family (or more?) for a considerable part of the year, well the choice should be clear.  </p>
<p>I say this as a vegan with total contempt for sport-hunting.  But hunting for sustenance, I can at least understand the rationale.  And to another poster's comment, I fully agree that the only meat one should eat that which you've killed yourself.  There's infinitely more honor and respect in such a thing than someone who gets their low-fat chicken salad from the factory farm and speaks nastily about hunting.  </p>
<p>Are a lot of hunters insensitive cretins?  In my experience, yes.  But I also know those who observe a code of conduct and honor about it all, even if I don't agree with it.  And if this is a means to practice a more accurate, immediate killshot, well the animal is going to suffer as briefly as possible.  And hopefully their sacrifice is appreciated and respected.</p>
    </div>
