<div class="indented"><a id="comment-2078420"></a>


<div  id="comment-2078420" class="comment comment-published clear-block">
      <div class='column-top'><div class='column-wrapper'>
  
      <div class='comment-submitted clear-block'> <div class='byline'>Posted by <span class='username'>wary</span></div><div class='date'>Mar 14 2012 - 7:47pm</div></div>
  
      </div></div>
  
      <div class='column-main'><div class='column-wrapper'>
  


      <div class='comment-content clear-block prose'>
      <p>For all the horrors of factory animal farming, one good aspect of it is that it DOES reduce the killing of animals to a detached, mechanized process - none (save a few very sick human minds) get satisfaction from any aspect of the animal killing and delivery process on farms.  It's a grim reality unattended by any hoopla, testosterone, or bragging.</p>
<p>Hunters, on the other hand, DO enjoy the slaughter of animals they shoot, whether by gun or bow and arrow.  They enjoy the methodology; they enjoy the equipment; they enjoy the tactics, the stalking, the laying of the trap.  Even the ones who will soberly tell you that hunting is just a fact of obtaining nutrition from the land - they're full of shit, because they enjoy it too.  They have the choice, just like all of us, to obtain their nutrition from plants.  But they choose to git in their trucks, or pull on their gear, oil up the guns, and go be hunter boys in the trees for a few hours or a few days.</p>
<p>The gun worship, sometimes thinly veiled as "respect for the tools", always gives it away.</p>
<p>People who work in slaughterhouses, I can almost guarantee, don't go home to brag about their kills for the day.  They also don't dress it up in insincere language about the "beauty of the animals" they killed, and they don't imagine themselves to be modern day noble natives.  That shit is all a dodge.  It's the grim work of killing animals to feed the grossly swollen human population on this planet that they do.</p>
<p>Everyone who kills animals has the choice not to eat animal meat, except in emergency situations which don't happen very often near civilization.</p>
<p>I have much more respect for trappers, who don't participate immediately in stalking prey, and who thus don't get their little hard-ons from the thrill of the chase, the power of the gun recoil, and the sight of the animal dropping.  Trapping has other drawbacks, though, and usually results in a lot of pain to animals.</p>
    </div>
      <div class='comment-links clear-block'><ul class="links"><li class="comment_forbidden first last"><span><a href="/user/login?destination=node%2F80387%23comment-form">Login</a> or <a href="/user/register?destination=node%2F80387%23comment-form">register</a> to post comments</span></li>
