<div class="indented"><a id="comment-2078701"></a>


<div  id="comment-2078701" class="comment comment-published clear-block">
      <div class='column-top'><div class='column-wrapper'>
  
      <div class='comment-submitted clear-block'> <div class='byline'>Posted by <span class='username'>wary</span></div><div class='date'>Mar 15 2012 - 1:20am</div></div>
  
      </div></div>
  
      <div class='column-main'><div class='column-wrapper'>
  


      <div class='comment-content clear-block prose'>
      <p>Even native hunts ended with animals slaughtered by people who got some degree of thrill out of it.</p>
<p>I don't believe modern slaughterhouse workers are actually numb to killing, unless they are already compromised, hurting individuals.  Slaughterhouse work actively degrades the spirit - it has to - and thus there's a feedback loop which has a hope to end it.</p>
<p>A danger there is that more and more aspects of factory farming could be mechanized, further removing humans from intimate exposure to the process.  To a large extent most consumers already are, but there are still key workers needed to perform the killing.</p>
<p>I'll cut native hunters a lot of slack because their ways of life are or were so much less harmful overall.  Depending on where they lived, they might not have been able to obtain enough nutrition from growing plants (and there were far less people).  That's rarely an issue in modern civilization, where agricultural methods, even smart ones, are known and food can be transported moderate distances to people in remote areas.  Virtually no one in American society anymore needs to slaughter animals in any way to live.</p>
    </div>
