</div></div><a id="comment-2078686"></a>


<div  id="comment-2078686" class="comment comment-published clear-block">
      <div class='column-top'><div class='column-wrapper'>
  
      <div class='comment-submitted clear-block'> <div class='byline'>Posted by <span class='username'>wary</span></div><div class='date'>Mar 15 2012 - 1:05am</div></div>
  
      </div></div>
  
      <div class='column-main'><div class='column-wrapper'>
  


      <div class='comment-content clear-block prose'>
      <p>Enjoyment of an ethically problematic act complicates and magnifies the evil of the act and the person performing it, and that enjoyment makes it more likely that the act will be rationalized and continue.</p>
<p>We can theoretically see an end to a practice like factory farming, when the spirit is so worn down by the banal, workaday, completely unrewarding slaughter that society eventually refuses to continue doing it.  Not so with hunting, an act almost always performed by people who RELISH it, fetishize and ritualize it to varying degrees, and often rationalize it as necessary, or even devotional to nature, etc.  That's when all hope is lost.</p>
<p>The more philosophical hunting promoters say it's a more "conscious" way to kill and therefore ethically superior.  I say they're more conscious of the primal thrill triggers involved in hunting down and taking life, and that they're heaping on layers of ideological justification for an act which basically just feels good and "right" and "natural" to them.</p>
<p>All this is why celebration of the urge to use powered projectiles against animals is loathsome.</p>
    </div>
