      <div class='column-main'><div class='column-wrapper'>
  


      <div class='comment-content clear-block prose'>
      <p>Yes, actually a good idea.  Ethical shot placement is a very important concept.  Abby, if people are going to hunt, would you prefer the animals die quickly from a quick clean kill or are shot in the gut and suffer for days before dying?  Ethical hunters will not shoot unless they are confident they can kill the animal.  Very important skill.</p>
<p>I think posts like this are the reason the left has so much trouble attracting support from my rural neighbors.  When I killed a deer last fall, it was not so much of an adrenaline rush as a bittersweet opportunity for thoughtful introspection about the web of life and human privilege and stuff like that.  </p>
<p>But you got your snark on, and hunters and non-hunters alike continue to be screwed by the 1% and do good liberals can pat themselves on the back for keeping the 99% divided.</p>
<p>There's actually lots of interesting discussion to be had around these issues, like whether it's ethical to eat meat one didn't kill (I don't think it is), the value of free range hormone free game, whether trophy killing is ethical (I don't think it is),  but I doubt those conversations will ever happen here, nor will this become a page that could actually threaten the white-supremecist, capitalist patriarchy that's actually destroying our planet.</p>
    </div>
